Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The intersection of fairness, utility, and differential privacy (DP) in agent-item allocation systems—such as recommendation engines, resource distribution platforms, or matching markets—is underexplored, especially when privacy is enforced at the fine-grained (agent × item)-level. Existing work either treats privacy and fairness separately (e.g., Paper 3 shows strong negative results for fairness under strict DP adjacency) or focuses on model-level privacy in learning (Papers 1 and 2), without considering how utility functions themselves can be structurally adapted to preserve both privacy and fairness simultaneously. My key insight is that instead of applying privacy *post hoc* via noise addition or gradient clipping, we should *co-design* the utility function with built-in robustness to local perturbations induced by (agent × item)-level DP, while embedding fairness constraints directly into the functional form. This shifts the paradigm from "private learning of standard utilities" to "learning inherently private-fair utilities." By leveraging tempered transformations—bounded, smooth, and sensitivity-controlled functional components inspired by tempered sigmoids—we can design utility functions whose outputs are intrinsically less sensitive to individual agent-item disclosures. Furthermore, integrating adaptive fairness regularization—learned across heterogeneous tasks, akin to meta-learning approaches in Paper 2—allows the system to generalize fairness under privacy stress. This approach uniquely bridges architectural design (Paper 1), adaptive protection (Paper 2), and fair allocation theory (Paper 3), but goes beyond all by proposing a unified utility space where privacy, fairness, and utility are jointly optimized through structural inductive biases rather than external mechanisms.

